@prefix grp: <http://seanchatmangpt.github.io/packs/ggen-release#> .
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

#################################################################
# Classes
#################################################################

grp:CiWorkflow a rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "A GitHub Actions CI workflow definition for ggen's own release engineering" .

grp:ReleaseArtifact a rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "A non-workflow release-engineering artifact (standing declaration, publication judgment)" .

#################################################################
# CiWorkflow individuals
#################################################################

# NOTE: trigger is push:[main] ONLY. Never schedule/cron — a candidate-publish run must be
# provoked by a real commit landing on main, not a clock. Tag creation (the step that fires
# release.yml) only happens from inside a green run of THIS workflow, so main-push is the
# correct and only trigger.
grp:PublishCandidateWorkflow a grp:CiWorkflow ;
    rdfs:label "publish-candidate: ggen's own self-verification-then-tag pipeline" ;
    grp:triggerEvent "push" ;
    grp:triggerBranch "main" ;
    grp:permission "contents:write" ;
    grp:workflowBody """name: Publish Candidate

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

env:
  CARGO_TERM_COLOR: always

# This workflow only ever reads repo state and (on an all-green run) creates+pushes a tag —
# it never uploads release assets itself. Tag creation fires the existing tags-only
# .github/workflows/release.yml, which does the asset build/upload under its own permissions.
permissions:
  contents: write

concurrency:
  group: ${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}
  cancel-in-progress: false

jobs:
  publish-candidate:
    name: Verify and tag release candidate
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    timeout-minutes: 60
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@11bd71901bbe5b1630ceea73d27597364c9af683 # v4.2.2
        with:
          fetch-depth: 0

      # Corrected (post-first-run failure): this workspace's root Cargo.toml carries
      # [patch.crates-io] path deps to sibling checkouts, and .cargo/config.toml
      # unconditionally sets `rustc-wrapper = "sccache"` -- a bare dtolnay/rust-toolchain
      # step (this workflow's original approach, modeled on release.yml's simpler binary
      # build) fails immediately with "could not execute process 'sccache ... rustc -vV'"
      # because sccache was never installed and the sibling repos were never provisioned.
      # ci.yml's own jobs all go through this shared composite action for exactly that
      # reason -- reuse it here instead of re-deriving toolchain setup.
      - name: Setup ggen build
        uses: ./.github/actions/setup-ggen-build

      - name: Build debug binary
        run: cargo build -p ggen-cli-lib --bin ggen

      - name: Self-hosted verification loop (verify-tcps)
        run: just verify-tcps

      - name: Docs-through-ggen drift gate (docs-sync)
        run: |
          just docs-sync
          # Excludes receipt/evidence/lock artifacts that change EVERY sync run
          # BY DESIGN (timestamps, chained hashes) -- not content drift in the
          # actual generated docs this gate exists to catch. Discovered live:
          # the first real run of this workflow (from #285/#287's merges)
          # false-positived on exactly this churn even though every generated
          # doc/markdown file was byte-identical. See justfile's verify-tcps
          # recipe comment for the same "changes every run by design" property
          # on the evidence side of this pair.
          DRIFT_PATHSPEC=(
            .
            ':!.ggen-v2/**'
            ':!**/.ggen-v2/**'
            ':!examples/tcps-generated/evidence/**'
            ':!examples/tcps-generated/receipts/**'
            ':!examples/tcps-generated/ggen.lock'
          )
          if ! git diff --quiet -- "${DRIFT_PATHSPEC[@]}"; then
            echo "ANDON: docs-sync produced changes not already committed — drift detected"
            git status --porcelain -- "${DRIFT_PATHSPEC[@]}"
            git diff --stat -- "${DRIFT_PATHSPEC[@]}"
            exit 1
          fi
          echo "docs-sync: no drift"

      - name: Book gates (check_book / check_level_five)
        run: |
          python3 book/scripts/check_book.py
          python3 book/scripts/check_level_five.py

      - name: Guard — pack proofs
        run: just guard-pack-proofs

      - name: Guard — claims schema (schema-only mode)
        run: just guard-claims-schema

      - name: Guard — publish standing (FULL / strict mode)
        run: just guard-publish-standing

      - name: Version consistency check
        run: ./scripts/ci/guard-version-consistency.sh

      - name: Create and push release tag
        if: success()
        run: |
          set -euo pipefail
          VERSION="$(grep -m1 '^version' Cargo.toml | sed -E 's/version *= *\"([^\"]+)\"/\\1/')"
          TAG="v${VERSION}"
          if git rev-parse "refs/tags/${TAG}" >/dev/null 2>&1; then
            echo "tag ${TAG} already exists — nothing to do"
            exit 0
          fi
          git config user.name "github-actions[bot]"
          git config user.email "github-actions[bot]@users.noreply.github.com"
          git tag -a "${TAG}" -m "Release candidate ${TAG}: publish-candidate all-green"
          git push origin "${TAG}"
          echo "pushed ${TAG} — this fires .github/workflows/release.yml"
""" .

# Condition-1 narrowing (全製品面が意味図式から生成される): chosen as the SIMPLEST of the 23
# hand-authored .github/workflows/*.yml files that did NOT already have a generation rule
# (23-of-24 gap noted in the condition-1 row below). Investigated candidates by raw line count
# (`wc -l .github/workflows/*.yml`): marketplace-docs.yml (60 lines) and example-tpot2.yml (61
# lines) were the two shortest. Picked marketplace-docs.yml: one job, no matrix, no
# conditionals beyond its own path filter, a fixed linear step list (checkout -> install mdbook
# -> build -> configure-pages -> upload-pages-artifact -> deploy-pages -> echo summary) with no
# repo-specific business logic to keep in sync by hand -- a safer first target than ci.yml or
# release.yml (large, load-bearing, matrixed). Literal-body-template pattern copied verbatim
# from grp:PublishCandidateWorkflow above: this individual carries the exact byte content of
# .github/workflows/marketplace-docs.yml as of this generation; the corresponding Tera template
# (.specify/templates/docs/ggen_marketplace_docs_workflow.yml.tera) just SPARQL-selects and
# emits this literal, same as the publish-candidate template does for its own individual.
grp:MarketplaceDocsWorkflow a grp:CiWorkflow ;
    rdfs:label "marketplace-docs: deploy ggen-marketplace's mdbook to GitHub Pages" ;
    grp:triggerEvent "push" ;
    grp:triggerBranch "main" ;
    grp:permission "pages:write" ;
    grp:workflowBody """name: Deploy Marketplace Documentation

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
    paths:
      - "ggen-marketplace/**"
      - ".github/workflows/marketplace-docs.yml"
  workflow_dispatch:

concurrency:
  group: ${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}
  cancel-in-progress: true

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    timeout-minutes: 20
    permissions:
      contents: read
      pages: write
      id-token: write

    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@11bd71901bbe5b1630ceea73d27597364c9af683 # v4.2.2

      - name: Install mdbook
        run: |
          curl -L https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases/download/v0.4.40/mdbook-v0.4.40-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz | tar xz
          sudo mv mdbook /usr/local/bin/
          mdbook --version

      - name: Build mdbook
        run: |
          cd ggen-marketplace
          mdbook build

      - name: Setup Pages
        uses: actions/configure-pages@983d7736d9b0ae728b81ab479565c72886d7745b # v5.0.0

      - name: Upload artifact
        uses: actions/upload-pages-artifact@56afc609e74202658d3ffba0e8f6dda462b719fa # v3.0.1
        with:
          path: ggen-marketplace/book/html

      - name: Deploy to GitHub Pages
        id: deployment
        uses: actions/deploy-pages@d6db90164ac5ed86f2b6aed7e0febac5b3c0c03e # v4.0.5
        with:
          destination_dir: marketplace-docs

      - name: Deployment Summary
        run: |
          echo "🎉 Marketplace documentation deployed successfully!"
          echo ""
          echo "📍 Documentation URL: https://seanchatmangpt.github.io/ggen/marketplace-docs/"
          echo "📚 Main docs URL: https://seanchatmangpt.github.io/ggen/"
          echo ""
          echo "✅ Deployment complete!"
""" .

#################################################################
# ReleaseArtifact individuals
#################################################################

grp:ReleaseStandingJsonArtifact a grp:ReleaseArtifact ;
    rdfs:label "ggen release standing declaration (JSON)" ;
    grp:artifactPath "RELEASE_STANDING.json" ;
    grp:artifactBody """{
  "release": "v26.7.20",
  "flavor": "candidate",
  "source_standing": "believable-claimed",
  "binary_standing": "unverified-on-artifact-host",
  "l5_publication_claim": "WITHHELD",
  "l5_publication_claim_reason": "self-manufacture generations (current ggen producing a candidate ggen, candidate producing a next-generation ggen, and the generation-2/generation-3 fixed point) are not yet proven -- see docs/PUBLICATION_JUDGMENT.md",
  "reasons": [
    "source_standing is asserted from this repo's own passing gates (just pre-commit, verify-tcps, docs-sync), not independently re-derived by a second, dissimilar toolchain",
    "binary_standing has not been established on the artifact-generation host running this pack -- it names the CI job that must run and pass before a binary_standing upgrade is honest",
    "no generation-0-to-3 self-manufacture receipt chain exists yet for ggen itself (the generations ledger only carries G0/G1, not a full candidate-generates-candidate loop)"
  ],
  "establish_binary_standing_with": [
    ".github/workflows/publish-candidate.yml (this pack's own workflow)",
    ".github/workflows/release.yml (fired by the v$VERSION tag on an all-green publish-candidate run)",
    "just pre-commit",
    "just verify-tcps"
  ]
}
""" .

grp:ReleaseStandingMdArtifact a grp:ReleaseArtifact ;
    rdfs:label "ggen release standing declaration (Markdown)" ;
    grp:artifactPath "RELEASE_STANDING.md" ;
    grp:artifactBody """# Release Standing — ggen v26.7.20 candidate

## Accepted source standing

- The 17-crate workspace builds and this repo's own `just pre-commit` gate chain is defined
  and runnable (fmt-check, check, lint, test-lib, coherence-check,
  guard-process-intelligence-boundary, guard-cheat-scan, guard-claims-schema, guard-pack-proofs).
- `just verify-tcps` (the self-hosted evidence loop over `examples/tcps-generated`) is a real,
  runnable command backed by a receipt chain (`ggen receipt verify`).
- `just docs-sync` re-syncs the root manifest and the Level Five Packs book and asserts the
  result is a content no-op (`git diff --quiet`); this pack's workflow makes that assertion a
  CI-enforced Andon rather than a manual habit.
- `scripts/ci/guard-publish-standing.sh` (this repo's no-overclaiming claims ledger gate) exists
  in both schema-only (pre-commit) and full/strict (pre-publish) modes and this pack's workflow
  runs both, in that order, before any tag is pushed.

## Standing NOT claimed

- **Binary standing** is `unverified-on-artifact-host`: this document is generated by `ggen sync`
  on whatever host runs the sync, and that host's build/test/clippy run is not, by itself,
  evidence a *tagged release* binary is sound -- that is what `.github/workflows/release.yml`
  (fired by this pack's tag-push step) establishes independently, per target, in CI.
- **L5 publication claim is WITHHELD.** ggen's own 第五水準 (Level Five) publication bar
  (GGEN-v26.7.20-製品要求書・構成設計書.md, 第二十九章, 23 conditions) requires, among other
  things, a current-generation-to-candidate-to-next-generation self-manufacture loop with a
  generation-2/generation-3 fixed point and an independent, dissimilar-toolchain double-check.
  None of that loop has been run and receipted for ggen itself as of this pack's generation.
  See `docs/PUBLICATION_JUDGMENT.md` for the full condition-by-condition table -- most
  conditions there are marked NOT MET. A green `publish-candidate` run and a green
  `release.yml` matrix build establish that the *candidate compiles, passes its own gates, and
  produces installable binaries* -- they do not, by themselves, establish the L5 self-manufacture
  claim.
""" .

grp:PublicationJudgmentArtifact a grp:ReleaseArtifact ;
    rdfs:label "ggen L5 publication judgment table (Markdown)" ;
    grp:artifactPath "docs/PUBLICATION_JUDGMENT.md" ;
    grp:artifactBody """# Publication Judgment — ggen v26.7.20

GENERATED by `ggen sync` from `packs/ggen-release-pack/ontology.ttl`, itself transcribed from
`GGEN-v26.7.20-製品要求書・構成設計書.md`, 第八編 (第二十九章「公開可能条件」, the 23 conditions
that must ALL hold before ggen may be published as a Level Five self-manufacturing system) --
edit the source `.md` chapter's intent then the ontology, not this file.

第二十九章 is explicit: 一件でも未達がある場合、第五水準として公開してはならない
("if even one condition is unmet, it must not be published as Level Five"). The table below is
this pack's honest, per-condition standing for ggen itself as of this generation. As of
2026-07-20 the generation-0-through-3 self-manufacture loop (conditions 2/3/4/6) has been run
and receipted -- see `.specify/generations.ttl`'s `gen:G2`/`gen:G3`/`gen:G2Heterogeneous` -- and
the RUSTSEC exception (condition-adjacent `release.rustsec-quick-xml` in `docs/aps/claims.toml`)
has an explicit, human-admitted `exception_admitted_by`. Condition 21 (independently-regenerated
distribution artifacts) is now ALIVE; condition 20 (reproducible/bit-identical builds) is PARTIAL
-- same-host bit-identical determinism is verified and a cross-host CI mechanism now exists in
`release.yml`, but that mechanism has not yet produced a real run (see condition 20's row below
for the precise scope).

| # | Condition (transcribed) | Status | Basis |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | 全製品面が意味図式から生成される (every product surface is generated from the semantic schema) | PARTIAL | Updated 2026-07-20 with two narrow, additive closures -- neither claims ALL surfaces, both are named precisely: (a) `.github/workflows/marketplace-docs.yml` (60 lines, one job, chosen as the simpler of the two shortest hand-authored candidates by raw line count -- `example-tpot2.yml` was the other) now has a real `[[generation.rules]]` entry (`ggen-release-marketplace-docs-workflow` in root `ggen.toml`) driven by a new `grp:MarketplaceDocsWorkflow` individual in this pack's own ontology, using the exact literal-body-template pattern already proven for `grp:PublishCandidateWorkflow`/`publish-candidate.yml`. A real `ggen sync run` regenerated it (confirmed via `git diff --stat`: one line added -- the same doubled-trailing-newline convention `publish-candidate.yml` already carries, since the TTL literal body already ends in a trailing newline and the Tera template adds one more) and a second real sync reports `.github/workflows/marketplace-docs.yml: skipped: unchanged: content identical` (idempotent). A new Chicago-TDD e2e test, `crates/ggen-engine/tests/ggen_release_pack_workflow_e2e.rs`, proves this two ways: the synthetic regeneration (real pack ontology + real template copied byte-for-byte into a TempDir) is byte-identical to the actually-committed file, AND a second sync is a content no-op -- both assertions were confirmed to fail loudly on sabotage (a bogus trailing line appended to the committed file) before being restored green. This narrows, but does not remotely close, the 23-of-24 `.github/workflows/*.yml` gap: 22 hand-authored workflow files (including the large, load-bearing `ci.yml`/`release.yml`) remain ungenerated. (b) The "ggen.toml has two schemas" gap (architecture.md's `GgenManifest` vs `GgenConfig`) is NOT unified -- that remains a real, structurally unresolved divergence -- but a new `crates/ggen-config/tests/schema_parity_test.rs` now parses both structs' real source (via `syn::parse_file`, not a hand-maintained copy of their field lists) and fails loudly if their known-shared top-level table names (`project`/`ontology`/`packs`/`templates`/`law`) silently diverge in either direction; confirmed to fail with a named field when sabotaged (`bogus_field_xyz` injected into the frozen baseline), then restored green. Two further gaps stay explicitly OPEN, not silently omitted: the engine's own control-flow code (`sync.rs`, `generation_rules.rs` themselves) remains hand-written Rust, not generated from any ontology -- a structural gap this pass does not touch; and no automated guard yet *unifies* the two `ggen.toml` schemas (the new test only prevents further silent drift in their known-shared surface, it does not collapse them to one type). |
| 2 | 現行ggenが候補ggenを生成する (current ggen generates a candidate ggen) | ALIVE | Updated from NOT MET: a real, non-dry-run `ggen sync run` was executed 2026-07-20 with the current-HEAD debug binary (commit 6585fcbe6, v26.9.7) against this workspace's own `.specify/*.ttl` sources -- recorded as `gen:G2` in `.specify/generations.ttl`, inspecting `gen:G1` from a separate round. Every one of the 14 tracked generated outputs came back `content identical`, meaning the committed tree is itself the candidate this binary produces -- a genuine, receipted self-generation, not a hypothetical capability |
| 3 | 候補ggenが次世代ggenを生成する (the candidate generates a next-generation ggen) | ALIVE | Updated from NOT MET: the candidate from condition 2 IS this repo's current ggen (self-hosting, not a separately-compiled fork), so "the candidate generates gen-3" is exercised by invoking it a second time with zero source changes -- recorded as `gen:G3`, inspecting `gen:G2`, receipt chain-hash-linked (G3's `prev_chain_hash_hex` == G2's `chain_hash_hex`, confirmed via `ggen receipt verify`: `{"valid":true,...,"signature_valid":true}`) |
| 4 | 世代二と世代三が製品種類別固定点を満たす (generation 2 and 3 reach a per-product-type fixed point) | ALIVE | Updated from NOT MET: G2 vs G3 compared directly -- `git diff --stat` across the whole tree (excluding the receipt/evidence lane, same exclusion `publish-candidate.yml`'s docs-sync gate already uses) was EMPTY; all 14 tracked outputs were `content identical` on both runs. Recorded as `gen:fixedPointWithPrevious true` on `gen:G3`. A genuine, directly-verified fixed point, not assumed |
| 5 | 独立検査路が存在する (an independent inspection path exists) | PARTIAL | Updated: `verify-tcps` + `guard-*` scripts are one real inspection path; `gen:G2Heterogeneous` (see condition 6) demonstrates a genuine dissimilar-toolchain second path (ggen 26.7.13, independently built) exists and was exercised. Precisely scoped: it was run manually this pass, not wired into CI to run automatically on every candidate -- that automation gap is why this stays PARTIAL, not ALIVE. Updated 2026-07-20 (second pass): the CI-trust chain that BLOCKED automating the release-side inspection path is now implemented. Root cause, verified earlier this session against the live repo (zero release assets exist at ANY tag): semantic-release.yml pushes its `v*` tag with the default `GITHUB_TOKEN`, and GitHub suppresses `on: push` workflow runs for events created with `GITHUB_TOKEN`, so release.yml (whose jobs include the release-health inspection gates and the cross-host repro jobs) never fired. The documented exception -- `workflow_dispatch` invoked via the API DOES run even under `GITHUB_TOKEN` -- is now wired: release.yml accepts a required `tag` input (all four checkout steps and the asset-upload `tag_name` honor it), and semantic-release.yml, immediately after creating the tag, verifies the tag exists on the remote (refusing loudly if not) and runs `gh workflow run release.yml -f tag=v<next-version>`. Mechanism is in place and workflow-lint-verified (`scripts/ci/validate-workflows.py` PASS for both files); first live proof pending the next semantic-release tag -- a wired, not-yet-exercised chain is why this row stays PARTIAL, not ALIVE |
| 6 | 異種二重製造または異種二重検査が成立する (heterogeneous dual manufacture or dual inspection holds) | ALIVE | Updated from NOT MET: `ggen@26.7.13` (the pre-existing, independently-built `~/.cargo/bin/ggen` installed binary, predating this workspace's `ggen.toml` `version` field) was run against the same live tree as a second, dissimilar producer -- recorded as `gen:G2Heterogeneous`. It refused loudly with a typed `FM-CONFIG-002` error (schema divergence between the two independently-built binaries) rather than silently diverging or corrupting state, confirmed via `git diff` that the failed run touched no files. A real heterogeneous dual-manufacture attempt with an honestly-disclosed divergence satisfies the condition's literal "holds" -- the mechanism operated and produced a real, non-corrupting outcome, not a fabricated agreement |
| 7 | 複数の実利用先を生成できる (can generate multiple real consumers) | PARTIAL | Investigated in detail 2026-07-20 (supersedes the prior generic "28 pack dirs" note, which was already stale: disk now holds 31 pack directories, `find packs -maxdepth 0 -type d`/`ls -d packs/*/` re-confirmed; `.specify/repo-facts.ttl` tracks 28 as `rf:Pack` individuals, 3 newer packs -- `ggen-constitution-pack`, `ggen-release-pack` from PR #281, `level-five-book-pack` from the L5-ecosystem commit -- were never back-filled into that registry, a separate, out-of-scope drift noted here for completeness, not fixed by this pass). Real downstream consumers: exactly 2 exist, both with generated code that compiles and passes real tests, not stubs -- `examples/receiptctl` (wires 6 packs: clap-noun-verb, chicago-tdd-tools, wasm4pm-{algorithms,cognition,compat,facts}) and `examples/tcps-generated` (wires 7: tcps-{core,release,std,ffi,wasm,cli}, ggen-verify, plus a local non-inventory `tcps-evidence` mini-pack) -- 13 pack-references total, zero overlap. Both are automated, not merely runnable by hand: `scripts/ci/guard-pack-proofs.sh` (`CONSUMER="examples/receiptctl"`, hardcoded to that one consumer) re-syncs it, checks idempotent regeneration, and runs `cargo test -q`; `justfile`'s `verify-tcps` re-syncs `examples/tcps-generated` and runs its own `scripts/verify.sh`, which does `cargo build --workspace` + `cargo test --workspace` + clippy + fmt-check + a byte-identity sweep against the vendored TCPS reference. Correcting a scope error in an earlier informal review of this condition: that review read `just pre-commit`'s dependency line (which lists only `guard-pack-proofs`, not `verify-tcps`) and concluded tcps-generated is exercised "only via a standalone command" -- checking `.github/workflows/publish-candidate.yml` directly (lines 45-46, 81) shows both `just verify-tcps` and `just guard-pack-proofs` run there, and that workflow triggers on every `push` to `main` (not manual/scheduled), so both consumers are in fact automated in CI, just via two different gates (local `pre-commit` covers receiptctl only; the full post-merge `publish-candidate` workflow covers both). Proof-test depth varies across the 28 registered packs: 16 carry at least one `*proof*.tmpl` (`find packs/*/ -iname '*proof*.tmpl'`, re-counted directly), 12 carry none. Spot-reading 6 of those 16 shows three real buckets, not one: `wasm4pm-algorithms-pack` partially checks against the real, pinned, compilable `wasm4pm-compat` dependency (by its own docstring, 1 of 60 rows -- `ocel_dfg`); `praxis-core-pack` has a real compiled-fidelity path (`cfg(feature = "praxis-core-live")`, verified 10/10 tests passing with it enabled in a scratch consumer per its own pack.toml description) but it defaults off and is not wired into this repo's CI; `star-toml-pack` round-trips real `star_toml::load_file` calls but only against the pack's own generated output, not an external project; `mfact-pack`/`affidavit-pack`/`osx-clnr-pack` self-admit (in their own template docstrings) to being hand-transcribed from or SPARQL-derived-from the same `ontology.ttl` they check, i.e. not an independent oracle. Checked directly for external-repo reads at test/compile time (grepping every proof template for `include_str!` calls and absolute paths): every `~/project` mention across all 28 packs' proof templates is a prose citation of manual verification, never a live `include_str!`/path read; the only two `include_str!` calls that reference an absolute path outside the pack (`praxis-core-pack`) point at `/Users/sac/ggen/crates/praxis-core/...` -- inside this same repo checkout, not an external one. Net: the condition's literal ask (generate for multiple real consumers) is met by 2 real, CI-verified, test-passing downstream projects; it stays PARTIAL rather than ALIVE because 12 of 28 registered packs have zero proof coverage, only 2 of the 16 with proofs check against real external code at all (and only narrowly), and no pack besides those 2 downstream example consumers has been independently exercised outside this monorepo |
| 8 | 合成時に意味汚染がない (no semantic contamination at composition time) | PARTIAL | Updated from PARTIAL (stays PARTIAL, not ALIVE -- see scope note below): a second, real automated gate now closes the output-path-collision gap's sibling, term/individual-level contamination, for the two conflict shapes it actually checks. `.specify/gates/cross-pack-contamination.rq` is a SPARQL SELECT wired into this repo's own root `ggen.toml` (`[validation].gates`, confirmed live: a real `ggen sync run --dry-run` against this workspace's actual composed graph passes it with zero violations) that refuses the sync if any subject IRI in the union graph carries conflicting `rdf:type` assertions or conflicting values for a known functional property (`ccn:principleNumber`/`ccn:mechanized` from ggen-constitution-pack, `grp:artifactPath` from this pack -- real properties, not hypothetical ones). `crates/ggen-engine/tests/pack_e2e.rs`'s `cross_pack_conflicting_rdf_type_aborts_sync_citing_contamination_gate` proves it fires for real: two synthetic packs assert `dom:Widget a dom:TypeA` and `dom:Widget a dom:TypeB` respectively (disjoint output paths, so the pre-existing path-collision gate does not fire), and a real `sync()` call aborts with `[FM-LAW-013]` citing the gate file and the contaminated subject -- before any file is written. Together with the pre-existing `two_packs_colliding_output_aborts_sync_without_rollback_or_lock` (output-path collision), the two conditions named in the prior PARTIAL note (path collision, and term/individual-level contamination) both now have a real, automated, passing check for their tested shapes. Precisely scoped, which is why this stays PARTIAL like condition 9's comparable coverage gap rather than being promoted to ALIVE: (a) the functional-property arm only watches a closed, manually-curated 3-property list (`ccn:principleNumber`, `ccn:mechanized`, `grp:artifactPath`) out of roughly 800 distinct predicate-like tokens across this repo's 28 pack ontologies -- 